WEBVTT

1
00:00:17.640 --> 00:00:19.080
In this world.

2
00:00:19.880 --> 00:00:22.439
there are many years
where nothing changes.

3
00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:25.480
and then. everything changes at once.

4
00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:28.400
{\an8}The source sells it to Istanbul.

5
00:00:29.680 --> 00:00:31.719
{\an8}Istanbul sells it to us.

6
00:00:31.720 --> 00:00:34.440
{\an8}and we sell it to you.

7
00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:37.080
{\an8}This is how it works.

8
00:00:37.600 --> 00:00:40.400
{\an8}This is how it has always worked.

9
00:00:41.440 --> 00:00:42.440
But now.

10
00:00:43.240 --> 00:00:44.919
there is no Istanbul.

11
00:00:44.920 --> 00:00:47.960
Now. everything has changed.

12
00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:50.320
Who are you. then?

13
00:00:51.160 --> 00:00:52.320
Transport.

14
00:00:53.720 --> 00:00:55.080
That's a funny name.

15
00:00:57.240 --> 00:00:59.400
Fuck off. you Scouse cunt.

16
00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:03.759
[Carter scoffs]

17
00:01:03.760 --> 00:01:05.559
[quiet. tense music playing]

18
00:01:05.560 --> 00:01:08.999
- You've got the bollocks for it. mate.
- So what's the plan?

19
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:12.239
[Hakan] Now. there is
just us and the source.

20
00:01:12.240 --> 00:01:15.039
so… we go to the source.

21
00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:15.960
Where's that?

22
00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:18.840
Pakistan.

23
00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:22.880
[Aziz] Can you transport it from there?

24
00:01:23.400 --> 00:01:26.039
Easy. I just need to know when
and how much I'm moving.

25
00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:27.999
We go in a few days.

26
00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.399
- Who's we?
- [Hakan] Everybody in this room.

27
00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:35.559
Everybody who knows this is happening
will be with us until it has happened.

28
00:01:35.560 --> 00:01:38.160
- Will it work?
- [Mylonas] It will work.

29
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:48.200
[Hakan] What we are doing
has never been done before.

30
00:01:49.520 --> 00:01:54.000
And will never be done again.
So let's show ambition.

31
00:01:55.080 --> 00:01:59.040
We go to the source.
and we bring back two.

32
00:01:59.640 --> 00:02:01.120
200 kilos?

33
00:02:01.920 --> 00:02:03.400
Two tonnes.

34
00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:06.720
[music intensifying]

35
00:02:20.760 --> 00:02:21.720
Two tonnes?

36
00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:24.639
That would have a street value
of at least £100 million.

37
00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:25.759
Worth a go then.

38
00:02:25.760 --> 00:02:29.639
It's nearly as much heroin
as Britain's annual usage.

39
00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:32.519
If it gets in.
then the price plummets. usage booms.

40
00:02:32.520 --> 00:02:35.119
and drugs deaths go off the charts.

41
00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:37.879
It won't get in
because I'm bringing it in.

42
00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:39.239
[Bailey] Who's going to Pakistan?

43
00:02:39.240 --> 00:02:41.600
Your Liverpool lot are coming.
if that's what you're asking.

44
00:02:42.360 --> 00:02:43.679
What's your plan?

45
00:02:43.680 --> 00:02:47.959
I go with them to Karachi to get
the deal done. then I bring back the load.

46
00:02:47.960 --> 00:02:50.479
When I deliver it back to 'em.
we nick 'em all. seize the drugs.

47
00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:51.720
and then we can all go home.

48
00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:54.960
I would need to request
official cover for this.

49
00:02:55.760 --> 00:02:57.519
Just asking for it might be the end of us.

50
00:02:57.520 --> 00:02:58.719
[Guy] This <i>is</i> the end of us!

51
00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:01.519
They won't do two tonnes again.
No one will.

52
00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:04.240
And we'll either catch 'em
or get found out tryin'.

53
00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:07.920
This is how it ends. one way or another.

54
00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:10.520
[Don] What do you need first?

55
00:03:12.760 --> 00:03:13.760
Sailors.

56
00:03:15.680 --> 00:03:20.039
My mate Pete works in Customs quarantine.
which basically means nicking parrots.

57
00:03:20.040 --> 00:03:22.119
Luckily for us.
he's bored out of his skull.

58
00:03:22.120 --> 00:03:24.879
- Concentrate on the matter in hand--
- Pete's ex-Special Boat Service.

59
00:03:24.880 --> 00:03:28.359
And so are his mates. And if we give them
every penny we've got.

60
00:03:28.360 --> 00:03:30.359
they reckon
they can get a boat to Karachi.

61
00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:31.840
[Blake] Would they be armed?

62
00:03:32.640 --> 00:03:35.000
I'm sorry. sir. I didn't hear that bit.

63
00:03:36.040 --> 00:03:38.159
- [Blake sighs]
- Ah! There you are.

64
00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:39.999
Like lambs to the slaughter.

65
00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:43.560
- We have a meeting. Home Secretary.
- You do. but not with me.

66
00:03:47.320 --> 00:03:51.759
[woman] It's a long route. Mr. Blake.
from your corner of government to mine.

67
00:03:51.760 --> 00:03:54.279
and yet you appear
to have found a shortcut.

68
00:03:54.280 --> 00:03:58.879
which is to request the ability to operate
in Pakistan without interference

69
00:03:58.880 --> 00:04:02.879
and safe passage for a vessel
containing two tonnes of heroin

70
00:04:02.880 --> 00:04:05.279
from Karachi to Felixstowe Docks.

71
00:04:05.280 --> 00:04:08.600
I'm talking about the biggest drugs bust
Europe has ever seen

72
00:04:09.320 --> 00:04:13.079
and dismantling what would be the most
powerful drug cartel in British history.

73
00:04:13.080 --> 00:04:16.319
And risking
a major international incident.

74
00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:18.719
which could bring down
a government already on the ropes.

75
00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:21.279
With respect. this is not a job
for the security services.

76
00:04:21.280 --> 00:04:25.439
Both we and the Americans
have operatives in the field in Pakistan.

77
00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:28.199
It's dangerous.
it's fragile. it's delicate.

78
00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:31.159
And into that. you are suggesting

79
00:04:31.160 --> 00:04:34.560
that we send a bunch
of Customs officers in false mustaches.

80
00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:37.479
We would be sending ourselves.

81
00:04:37.480 --> 00:04:41.160
We can't afford false mustaches.
but you can lend us a couple if you like.

82
00:04:44.120 --> 00:04:45.359
[woman] All is not lost.

83
00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:48.439
Now that we're aware of your plans.
we're duty bound to get involved.

84
00:04:48.440 --> 00:04:51.759
- We answer to the Home Office.
- That is the system that you know.

85
00:04:51.760 --> 00:04:54.040
But there is another system
that you don't.

86
00:04:56.840 --> 00:05:01.279
[sighs] What I know is
that every government departmental head.

87
00:05:01.280 --> 00:05:03.839
whether they're in charge
of the railways or the spies.

88
00:05:03.840 --> 00:05:07.400
worries about two things. money and power.

89
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.479
The Berlin Wall is down.
Northern Ireland is heading for peace.

90
00:05:11.480 --> 00:05:15.279
and I suspect that causes you
a measure of existential concern

91
00:05:15.280 --> 00:05:17.119
about money and about power.

92
00:05:17.120 --> 00:05:21.400
Which I imagine has you seeking new roles

93
00:05:22.120 --> 00:05:25.960
and new responsibilities
that might shore up your position.

94
00:05:28.240 --> 00:05:31.479
We do have some spare capacity.
which is lucky for you

95
00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:34.840
because if you truly aim
to do as you say. we <i>will</i> be involved.

96
00:05:35.360 --> 00:05:37.879
either to keep an eye on you
while you're out there.

97
00:05:37.880 --> 00:05:41.560
or to coordinate
the repatriation of your team's bodies.

98
00:05:42.240 --> 00:05:44.639
I take it keeping an eye on us means him.

99
00:05:44.640 --> 00:05:47.239
seeing as he's sat there
and hasn't said a bloody word.

100
00:05:47.240 --> 00:05:49.599
[woman] As it happens.
Lawrence will be in Karachi.

101
00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:53.199
which is a tinderbox. but considerably
safer than the rest of Pakistan.

102
00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:54.999
We won't be leaving Karachi.

103
00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:56.640
Then you have half a chance.

104
00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:01.759
Don't you want our flight details?

105
00:06:01.760 --> 00:06:03.519
We have your flight details.

106
00:06:03.520 --> 00:06:05.680
[chuckles] Course you do.
Where are we staying. then?

107
00:06:06.880 --> 00:06:08.079
The Imperial Hotel.

108
00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:10.480
They're very good. aren't they?
What's my mother's name?

109
00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:12.799
[Lawrence] Gladys.

110
00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:14.040
What the fuck?

111
00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:35.359
What happened in London?

112
00:06:35.360 --> 00:06:39.119
What happened in London is we're going
to Pakistan to buy two tonnes of smack.

113
00:06:39.120 --> 00:06:41.520
- Who's going?
- Us and the Turks.

114
00:06:42.040 --> 00:06:43.440
And some Cockney prick.

115
00:06:47.360 --> 00:06:49.039
I spoke to my boss.

116
00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:51.759
We can provide new identities
for you and your family.

117
00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:55.639
- I don't need you. mate.
- Oh. really? So what's your plan?

118
00:06:55.640 --> 00:06:56.919
Humiliate him.

119
00:06:56.920 --> 00:06:58.399
Show the kids on the estates

120
00:06:58.400 --> 00:07:01.080
that being a dealer isn't
their way out of the estates.

121
00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:04.600
I'm gonna take down his money.
take down his drugs.

122
00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:08.080
Bust the whole operation
so that no one else can take it on.

123
00:07:09.120 --> 00:07:10.280
[shakily] And then…

124
00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:14.679
You probably don't wanna know
what I'm gonna do to him then.

125
00:07:14.680 --> 00:07:15.919
You don't have to do that.

126
00:07:15.920 --> 00:07:18.639
- I want him to know it was me.
- Then give him to us.

127
00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:21.920
With these new sentences.
Carter would get life.

128
00:07:22.440 --> 00:07:24.959
which means he'd spend
the rest of his life in a cell

129
00:07:24.960 --> 00:07:26.760
knowing it was you that put him there.

130
00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:29.960
And you. you'd spend
the rest of your life out here.

131
00:07:31.080 --> 00:07:32.200
With your family.

132
00:07:35.080 --> 00:07:37.240
You can guess what happens to grasses.

133
00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:39.880
I don't care about that.

134
00:07:40.840 --> 00:07:43.960
What would surprise you
is what happens to grasses' families.

135
00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:47.120
It's vicious. It's fucking medieval.

136
00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:49.480
You won't get caught.

137
00:07:50.760 --> 00:07:53.599
Because all I need you to do
is what Carter needs you to do.

138
00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:55.600
Make sure the deal gets done

139
00:07:56.920 --> 00:07:58.320
and protect Carter.

140
00:07:59.320 --> 00:08:03.039
Then we'll take down the deal.
and we'll take down Carter.

141
00:08:03.040 --> 00:08:06.599
- It's that easy. is it?
- If it was that easy. we wouldn't be here.

142
00:08:06.600 --> 00:08:07.880
[Eddie sighs]

143
00:08:09.120 --> 00:08:11.320
- We need to keep talking.
- No.

144
00:08:13.160 --> 00:08:14.720
Carter's a clever lad.

145
00:08:15.800 --> 00:08:17.999
I need as little of this
in me head as possible.

146
00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.280
or he'll see it.
and if he sees it. then I'm dead.

147
00:08:21.800 --> 00:08:24.279
And you won't find anyone else
stupid enough to do this.

148
00:08:24.280 --> 00:08:25.600
You're not stupid.

149
00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:29.280
You take down Carter… [sighs]

150
00:08:30.120 --> 00:08:31.239
…you'll be a hero.

151
00:08:31.240 --> 00:08:35.480
Oh. yeah. a smack dealer <i>and</i> a grass.
They'll build a bloody statue for me!

152
00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:42.719
I'll be over there.

153
00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:44.480
[quiet. tense music playing]

154
00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:46.560
In Pakistan?

155
00:08:47.200 --> 00:08:48.080
Yeah.

156
00:08:52.080 --> 00:08:53.920
I'll not help you with the Turks.

157
00:08:55.040 --> 00:08:56.359
With Carter. it's personal.

158
00:08:56.360 --> 00:08:59.000
- The Turks aren't my problem.
- Don't worry about the Turks.

159
00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:04.520
Do you have someone like me
in with the Turks?

160
00:09:06.240 --> 00:09:07.120
No.

161
00:09:13.280 --> 00:09:15.400
That's the first time you've lied to me.

162
00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:28.559
- [birdsong]
- [children shouting]

163
00:09:28.560 --> 00:09:29.520
[music fades]

164
00:09:33.480 --> 00:09:34.800
I packed them.

165
00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:37.839
I'm checking you remembered
what you're packing for.

166
00:09:37.840 --> 00:09:41.399
which means remembering
to check your bloody pockets.

167
00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:44.000
This is a receipt
for the garage round the corner.

168
00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:47.119
You should be doing this job. not me.

169
00:09:47.120 --> 00:09:48.080
I am doing it.

170
00:09:48.800 --> 00:09:52.919
We're all doing it. You don't walk out
the door and take this job with you.

171
00:09:52.920 --> 00:09:53.920
I know.

172
00:09:54.680 --> 00:09:55.600
Sorry.

173
00:09:58.640 --> 00:10:02.320
- What is it?
- This… this feels different.

174
00:10:03.440 --> 00:10:05.720
- [sighs]
- It is different.

175
00:10:10.240 --> 00:10:13.719
- I don't wanna know where you're going.
- That's lucky. 'cause I can't tell ya.

176
00:10:13.720 --> 00:10:14.840
[chuckles]

177
00:10:17.400 --> 00:10:18.960
But I wanna know how long.

178
00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:22.359
I need to have something. Guy.

179
00:10:22.360 --> 00:10:24.520
- [sighs]
- You need to leave us with something.

180
00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:26.960
Can't tell you that.

181
00:10:28.080 --> 00:10:29.960
'Cause it will be in my head…

182
00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:32.599
[sighs] …getting back for that.

183
00:10:32.600 --> 00:10:35.880
And I'm not going as me. I'm going as him.

184
00:10:39.560 --> 00:10:42.240
And he doesn't have
anything to get back for.

185
00:10:49.560 --> 00:10:50.840
What is he like?

186
00:10:56.840 --> 00:10:58.240
He had a good life.

187
00:10:59.040 --> 00:11:00.360
Then he lost it.

188
00:11:01.200 --> 00:11:02.439
And he wants it back.

189
00:11:02.440 --> 00:11:06.280
And to get it back.
he made one bad decision after another.

190
00:11:07.960 --> 00:11:09.519
And now here he is.

191
00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:10.800
[exhales]

192
00:11:11.680 --> 00:11:13.639
- You like him.
- It's not about liking 'im.

193
00:11:13.640 --> 00:11:15.720
It's about not fighting who he is.

194
00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:17.640
It's about

195
00:11:18.240 --> 00:11:20.080
understanding who he is

196
00:11:21.440 --> 00:11:23.199
and how he ended up that way.

197
00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:25.679
It's about believing every word he says.

198
00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:28.440
agreeing with every decision he makes.

199
00:11:29.680 --> 00:11:33.120
and knowing
he doesn't wanna be doing this.

200
00:11:33.640 --> 00:11:36.199
But if this is what needs to be done…

201
00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:37.839
[soft. poignant music playing]

202
00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:39.679
[closes zipper]

203
00:11:39.680 --> 00:11:41.400
…he'll do it well.

204
00:11:49.320 --> 00:11:51.160
Well enough to come home.

205
00:11:52.880 --> 00:11:54.840
- [sighs]
- You like him.

206
00:11:55.720 --> 00:11:56.960
And that's okay.

207
00:11:57.480 --> 00:12:00.320
As long as. one day. you can let him go.

208
00:12:03.040 --> 00:12:05.840
That's the one bit of this
that will be easy.

209
00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:20.519
[Erin] Civil Service health and safety
forms for foreign travel.

210
00:12:20.520 --> 00:12:24.079
If I could just draw your attention
to part three.

211
00:12:24.080 --> 00:12:27.199
"Do not fraternize
with local undesirable elements.

212
00:12:27.200 --> 00:12:29.559
do not place yourself in physical danger.

213
00:12:29.560 --> 00:12:32.639
and avoid spicy food on a working day."

214
00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:33.840
Are you taking the piss?

215
00:12:35.640 --> 00:12:39.040
If you cop it while you're over there. do
you want your missus to get your pension?

216
00:12:39.880 --> 00:12:41.000
Sign it.

217
00:12:44.840 --> 00:12:46.919
- Why's he signing?
- Why do you think?

218
00:12:46.920 --> 00:12:48.199
[Guy] Why's he going?

219
00:12:48.200 --> 00:12:50.720
I'm going because I work here.
just like you.

220
00:12:51.320 --> 00:12:53.919
Keep talking about me without
using my name. we'll have a problem.

221
00:12:53.920 --> 00:12:55.039
This ain't about you. mate.

222
00:12:55.040 --> 00:12:57.919
This is about me getting this done
and about me staying alive.

223
00:12:57.920 --> 00:13:00.119
and I don't know
how you being there helps that happen.

224
00:13:00.120 --> 00:13:02.439
which makes me think
there's something I don't know.

225
00:13:02.440 --> 00:13:04.319
[Don] He's coming.
That's all you need to know.

226
00:13:04.320 --> 00:13:06.279
What is it? What have you got?

227
00:13:06.280 --> 00:13:08.440
Operational independence.
that's what I got.

228
00:13:10.640 --> 00:13:12.199
You got someone on the Liverpool team.

229
00:13:12.200 --> 00:13:13.359
You need to focus.

230
00:13:13.360 --> 00:13:15.559
If you've got someone in there.
hats off to you.

231
00:13:15.560 --> 00:13:17.279
I mean that. But I need to know who it is.

232
00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:18.759
No. you don't need to know.

233
00:13:18.760 --> 00:13:22.279
Because if you do know about them.
and you get turned over and knocked about.

234
00:13:22.280 --> 00:13:25.119
you could give them up.
and it's my job to keep them safe.

235
00:13:25.120 --> 00:13:27.039
You sayin' I can't take
a bit of knockin' about?

236
00:13:27.040 --> 00:13:30.800
I think you're forgettin' who you are.
One of the good guys. believe it or not.

237
00:13:31.320 --> 00:13:34.359
My name is Guy Stanton.
My parents are dead.

238
00:13:34.360 --> 00:13:36.519
I'm divorced. No kids.

239
00:13:36.520 --> 00:13:40.400
I had a good business. but one thing led
to another. and now I transport drugs.

240
00:13:41.040 --> 00:13:43.919
And I'm good at it 'cause I'm desperate.

241
00:13:43.920 --> 00:13:47.479
And I'm angry. and I'm greedy.
and I don't have a moral bone in my body.

242
00:13:47.480 --> 00:13:49.759
So. no. I'm not one of the good guys.

243
00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:53.399
And if you think I'm one of the good guys.
if you act like I'm one of the good guys.

244
00:13:53.400 --> 00:13:55.199
then you could get me fucking killed.

245
00:13:55.200 --> 00:13:58.679
Don't worry. mate.
I can see exactly who you are.

246
00:13:58.680 --> 00:14:01.999
[Don] Pack it in. You've both got jobs
to do. and you need to respect the system.

247
00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.120
so stop asking questions
and get to the bloody airport.

248
00:14:13.360 --> 00:14:15.599
Don't you be doing
anything stupid over there.

249
00:14:15.600 --> 00:14:16.720
[chuckles] Huh.

250
00:14:17.560 --> 00:14:20.760
I'm more worried about the trouble you'll
get into back here without me around.

251
00:14:22.400 --> 00:14:24.800
- Take care. mate.
- Yeah. you too.

252
00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:27.839
Right. let's get started.

253
00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:31.079
I'm waiting for a fax.
but I've had a few ideas.

254
00:14:31.080 --> 00:14:34.239
- Might be a bit tricky.
- [Kate] I thought it might be.

255
00:14:34.240 --> 00:14:35.440
What are you two up to?

256
00:14:36.280 --> 00:14:39.479
- I think Carter's got a corrupt cop.
- [Don] I bet he does.

257
00:14:39.480 --> 00:14:40.559
And I'm gonna find him.

258
00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:43.119
- Not our job.
- It is if I make the cop our way in.

259
00:14:43.120 --> 00:14:45.359
If we see signs of police corruption.

260
00:14:45.360 --> 00:14:47.559
there are ways something like that
should play out.

261
00:14:47.560 --> 00:14:49.999
- Systems.
- I don't know what those systems are.

262
00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:54.559
But I'd guess that they're very slow
and. for what we're doing. very risky.

263
00:14:54.560 --> 00:14:56.919
So do you wanna tell me what they are?

264
00:14:56.920 --> 00:14:59.679
Or do you wanna go
on your little boys' trip.

265
00:14:59.680 --> 00:15:03.000
and one way or another. I'll have a bent
copper waiting for you when you get back?

266
00:15:05.400 --> 00:15:06.400
Good luck.

267
00:15:12.080 --> 00:15:14.080
[soft. wistful music playing]

268
00:15:31.960 --> 00:15:33.080
[Mylonas] Time to go.

269
00:15:36.200 --> 00:15:37.480
[chuckles]

270
00:15:46.360 --> 00:15:47.640
[sighs]

271
00:15:54.600 --> 00:15:58.519
You don't have to stay. if there's
someone waiting for you at home.

272
00:15:58.520 --> 00:15:59.560
For me?

273
00:16:00.280 --> 00:16:01.160
[Erin] No?

274
00:16:02.880 --> 00:16:06.120
I've had two types of relationships
in my life. mate.

275
00:16:06.640 --> 00:16:08.880
Bad and fuckin' awful.

276
00:16:11.480 --> 00:16:13.360
- You?
- God. no.

277
00:16:14.080 --> 00:16:17.039
- There's been a few proposals. obviously.
- Obviously.

278
00:16:17.040 --> 00:16:19.759
But I've really mastered the art
of the upbeat rejection.

279
00:16:19.760 --> 00:16:20.720
[Kate] Hmm.

280
00:16:21.240 --> 00:16:25.679
Here's what I wanna know. How did you end
up working as a Civil Service secretary?

281
00:16:25.680 --> 00:16:29.999
Because… you're smart enough
to be running the place.

282
00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:33.920
and. no offense. but you talk
like you should be running the place too.

283
00:16:34.920 --> 00:16:39.240
My dad made a lot of money.
then lost a lot of money. and

284
00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:42.360
life changed.

285
00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:49.919
And London can be a confusing place when
you're poor but sound like you're rich.

286
00:16:49.920 --> 00:16:50.960
[Kate] Hmm.

287
00:16:52.360 --> 00:16:56.199
I've… spent a long time

288
00:16:56.200 --> 00:16:58.760
trying to find somewhere
that didn't matter.

289
00:16:59.360 --> 00:17:00.920
I reckon you've found it.

290
00:17:01.840 --> 00:17:02.920
So do I.

291
00:17:04.280 --> 00:17:06.280
[whirring]

292
00:17:09.720 --> 00:17:12.639
So. how to get a list
of Liverpool police employees

293
00:17:12.640 --> 00:17:14.839
without Liverpool police finding out?

294
00:17:14.840 --> 00:17:17.399
The answer's in the question.
They're employees.

295
00:17:17.400 --> 00:17:18.959
So I went through National Insurance.

296
00:17:18.960 --> 00:17:21.000
- Which took a bit of doing. but--
- How many?

297
00:17:23.120 --> 00:17:25.000
- 900.
- 900?

298
00:17:25.600 --> 00:17:28.520
913. I was rounding down.

299
00:17:29.040 --> 00:17:30.000
For morale.

300
00:17:47.160 --> 00:17:49.680
- [phone ringing]
- [man shouting in Pashto]

301
00:17:50.600 --> 00:17:52.760
[men conversing in Pashto]

302
00:17:54.280 --> 00:17:55.280
What's happenin'?

303
00:17:57.440 --> 00:17:59.799
This is happening.

304
00:17:59.800 --> 00:18:01.640
[suspenseful music playing]

305
00:18:18.920 --> 00:18:21.360
<i>Wa alaikum assalam.</i> Hakan.

306
00:18:22.200 --> 00:18:24.200
[kisses] Aaah!

307
00:18:25.320 --> 00:18:26.480
[kisses]

308
00:18:29.400 --> 00:18:30.480
This

309
00:18:31.560 --> 00:18:33.520
is my son. Aziz.

310
00:18:34.040 --> 00:18:36.440
<i>- Assalamu alaikum.</i>
- It's an honor.

311
00:18:37.120 --> 00:18:39.000
And I told you about the others.

312
00:18:40.560 --> 00:18:41.759
[man] Ahem.

313
00:18:41.760 --> 00:18:45.320
[breathlessly] Mr. Afridi. uh…
we did not know you were coming.

314
00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:48.040
[Afridi] Good.

315
00:18:56.680 --> 00:18:59.400
- [Bailey] Who was that?
- Do you think it'll be spicy?

316
00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.399
- Sorry?
- [Don] You're in Pakistan on business.

317
00:19:02.400 --> 00:19:04.519
You're not thinking
about a bloke over there.

318
00:19:04.520 --> 00:19:07.760
You're thinking about
whether the food is gonna be spicy.

319
00:19:12.760 --> 00:19:15.280
You've come a long way. gentlemen.

320
00:19:17.200 --> 00:19:18.920
- We're here to do business.
- [Afridi] Uh-uh.

321
00:19:19.760 --> 00:19:24.640
Karachi has many ears and many eyes.
We do not talk of such things in Karachi.

322
00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:27.640
Where do we do it. then?

323
00:19:31.120 --> 00:19:34.039
[in Pashto] Do you trust these men. Hakan?

324
00:19:34.040 --> 00:19:36.680
This is what I am here to find out.

325
00:19:43.640 --> 00:19:48.080
[in English] If you want to come to the
source. then you must come to the source.

326
00:19:56.960 --> 00:19:58.720
[in Pashto] Come on. Get moving.

327
00:20:05.800 --> 00:20:07.080
Hurry!

328
00:20:07.760 --> 00:20:10.799
- [Bailey. in English] They're moving.
- [Don] Then we need to find out where.

329
00:20:10.800 --> 00:20:11.919
[man shouts in Pashto]

330
00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:14.759
- [Bailey. in English] Back in a bit.
- [Don] Where… where are you going?

331
00:20:14.760 --> 00:20:16.800
[man shouting in Pashto]

332
00:20:18.440 --> 00:20:20.639
- I'm going for a piss.
- They won't like that.

333
00:20:20.640 --> 00:20:21.759
I don't give a shit.

334
00:20:21.760 --> 00:20:25.239
We've not come halfway around the world
to be bossed around by that lot.

335
00:20:25.240 --> 00:20:26.800
[shouting in Pashto continues]

336
00:20:28.080 --> 00:20:30.760
- Wait here.
- No. you fucking wait here.

337
00:20:31.760 --> 00:20:33.480
'Kin tell me what to do.

338
00:20:34.040 --> 00:20:35.680
[man. in Pashto] Where are the bags?

339
00:20:36.920 --> 00:20:38.320
Move it!

340
00:20:48.360 --> 00:20:50.359
- [Eddie] We're going to the source.
- Where's that?

341
00:20:50.360 --> 00:20:54.799
I don't know. but if I don't come back.
you tell my wife I'm sorry for what I did

342
00:20:54.800 --> 00:20:56.160
and I tried to put it right.

343
00:20:58.560 --> 00:20:59.680
[Carter] Gotta go.

344
00:21:00.920 --> 00:21:02.240
All right. I'm coming.

345
00:21:15.560 --> 00:21:17.080
[exhales]

346
00:21:18.760 --> 00:21:19.960
We're going now?

347
00:21:20.480 --> 00:21:22.440
- [Mylonas] Yes.
- Good.

348
00:21:23.480 --> 00:21:25.360
You. take our bags.

349
00:21:26.280 --> 00:21:27.840
Strange place to bring the missus.

350
00:21:29.320 --> 00:21:30.400
She will help.

351
00:21:32.600 --> 00:21:34.679
[lively music playing]

352
00:21:34.680 --> 00:21:36.680
[horns blaring]

353
00:21:44.440 --> 00:21:46.360
[Bailey] They're going to the source.

354
00:21:47.600 --> 00:21:48.759
[Don] No. no. no. no. no.

355
00:21:48.760 --> 00:21:51.799
- Taxi? You need a taxi. sir?
- Yeah. yeah. taxi.

356
00:21:51.800 --> 00:21:54.239
- Just here. sir.
- Yeah. My friends are in those cars.

357
00:21:54.240 --> 00:21:56.599
- I need to follow them.
- Of course. sir. This is no problem.

358
00:21:56.600 --> 00:21:58.799
- What's this?
- Just here. sir.

359
00:21:58.800 --> 00:22:00.159
No. no. I… I've gotta go.

360
00:22:00.160 --> 00:22:02.680
[Scouse accent] Just get
in the fucking car. Don.

361
00:22:09.400 --> 00:22:11.719
We'll follow them as far
as we're safe to do so.

362
00:22:11.720 --> 00:22:14.279
- Which isn't far.
- [Don] Where are they going?

363
00:22:14.280 --> 00:22:16.279
[Lawrence] The Khyber.
The Pakistan-Afghan border.

364
00:22:16.280 --> 00:22:19.480
Which is bad. but not as bad
as who's taking them there.

365
00:22:20.160 --> 00:22:22.599
That was Ayub Afridi. tribal warlord.

366
00:22:22.600 --> 00:22:26.279
Suspected of drug smuggling. arms trading.
and funding terrorist activity.

367
00:22:26.280 --> 00:22:28.999
If we knew you were meeting him.
you wouldn't have got on the plane.

368
00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:30.879
If the Americans
knew you were meeting Afridi.

369
00:22:30.880 --> 00:22:32.839
you'd be involuntary
houseguests of the CIA.

370
00:22:32.840 --> 00:22:34.079
Then let's pull him out.

371
00:22:34.080 --> 00:22:36.559
That would mean a lethal firefight
in central Karachi.

372
00:22:36.560 --> 00:22:39.519
Destroy years of investigation by
multiple international security agencies.

373
00:22:39.520 --> 00:22:42.479
Listen. That is my boy in that car. Right?

374
00:22:42.480 --> 00:22:46.119
So stop telling me how buggered he is. and
tell me what I need to do to get him out.

375
00:22:46.120 --> 00:22:47.719
You can wait and you can hope.

376
00:22:47.720 --> 00:22:50.160
But if I was you.
then I would prepare for the worst.

377
00:22:51.200 --> 00:22:53.200
[ominous music playing]

378
00:23:02.560 --> 00:23:07.159
913. That's where we started.
Remember that.

379
00:23:07.160 --> 00:23:10.519
or you may not recognize the progress
we've made in whittling it down.

380
00:23:10.520 --> 00:23:11.759
Come on. mate. Hurry up.

381
00:23:11.760 --> 00:23:15.519
We've removed those who joined after the
first charges against Carter were dropped

382
00:23:15.520 --> 00:23:18.079
or left before
the most recent charges were dropped.

383
00:23:18.080 --> 00:23:21.519
along with anyone unlikely to have the
authority to interfere with his record.

384
00:23:21.520 --> 00:23:23.599
- Which has meant whittling the whole--
- How many?

385
00:23:23.600 --> 00:23:25.039
326.

386
00:23:25.040 --> 00:23:27.399
- [whispers] Fucking hell.
- That is what I was worried about.

387
00:23:27.400 --> 00:23:29.599
You're not recognizing
the progress we've made.

388
00:23:29.600 --> 00:23:33.879
If we build more filters.
then we can keep whittling it down and--

389
00:23:33.880 --> 00:23:36.440
Please stop saying whittling. okay?
Please stop saying whittling.

390
00:23:39.280 --> 00:23:41.800
326 and

391
00:23:43.280 --> 00:23:45.160
us. [sighs heavily]

392
00:23:48.680 --> 00:23:50.320
[Kate sighs] Hmm.

393
00:23:56.640 --> 00:23:57.800
[sighs]

394
00:23:59.000 --> 00:24:00.960
We're looking at it the wrong way.

395
00:24:02.320 --> 00:24:06.600
Someone within Liverpool police
has been protecting Carter.

396
00:24:07.120 --> 00:24:10.880
That means stopping charges
being pressed. That has to leave a trail.

397
00:24:11.560 --> 00:24:14.799
He may not have a criminal record.
but he must have a police record.

398
00:24:14.800 --> 00:24:17.959
So we start with the police record
and then we look for the trail.

399
00:24:17.960 --> 00:24:20.599
There is no police record on the system.

400
00:24:20.600 --> 00:24:23.800
Which is interesting.
because who puts the record on the system?

401
00:24:24.400 --> 00:24:26.160
Liverpool police.

402
00:24:26.680 --> 00:24:28.039
We need the hard copy.

403
00:24:28.040 --> 00:24:30.799
That would mean putting a request
through their liaison office

404
00:24:30.800 --> 00:24:32.440
who would ask why we need it.

405
00:24:36.560 --> 00:24:38.519
I'll go back to Liverpool
and ask for it myself.

406
00:24:38.520 --> 00:24:40.839
- That feels dangerous. Kate.
- Do you know what. Erin?

407
00:24:40.840 --> 00:24:43.879
The best part of this job
is that no one's done it before.

408
00:24:43.880 --> 00:24:47.240
It feels important. exciting.

409
00:24:47.760 --> 00:24:51.399
And the hardest part of this job
is that no one has done it before.

410
00:24:51.400 --> 00:24:55.239
which means. every day. we have to make
decisions that no one has made before.

411
00:24:55.240 --> 00:24:57.559
What to do. where to go. who to target.

412
00:24:57.560 --> 00:25:00.040
Uh. I think. <i>I think.</i> I've cracked it.

413
00:25:00.560 --> 00:25:04.440
You look at all your options.
you find the danger.

414
00:25:06.120 --> 00:25:07.520
and you go towards it.

415
00:25:08.080 --> 00:25:10.080
["A Forest" by The Cure playing]

416
00:25:13.760 --> 00:25:15.760
[grasshoppers chirping]

417
00:26:22.960 --> 00:26:24.839
[in Pashto] Where does the woman sleep?

418
00:26:24.840 --> 00:26:27.320
[Zahra] She sleeps with her husband.

419
00:26:29.360 --> 00:26:31.840
And I have a job for you.

420
00:26:32.640 --> 00:26:33.799
Of course.

421
00:26:33.800 --> 00:26:34.759
[music fades]

422
00:26:34.760 --> 00:26:36.720
[Afridi. in English] This is what happens.

423
00:26:37.240 --> 00:26:39.679
This is what has always happened.

424
00:26:39.680 --> 00:26:44.920
Men like you come here with a plan.
and then things change.

425
00:26:47.160 --> 00:26:48.680
Many years ago.

426
00:26:49.200 --> 00:26:55.000
the British Army came and told my
grandfather that they had made a new map.

427
00:26:55.600 --> 00:26:59.080
And now we had to leave our mountains.

428
00:27:00.560 --> 00:27:04.240
The last of those British soldiers
died together

429
00:27:04.760 --> 00:27:06.079
on the top of a mountain.

430
00:27:06.080 --> 00:27:10.600
with their flags.
and their trumpets. and their plan.

431
00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:16.960
When the Russians came.
they said we were communists now.

432
00:27:19.920 --> 00:27:23.280
The last of those Russians.
we did not kill.

433
00:27:24.120 --> 00:27:27.279
They blew themselves up with grenades

434
00:27:27.280 --> 00:27:30.440
after they saw what we did to the others.

435
00:27:31.840 --> 00:27:33.479
When the Americans came.

436
00:27:33.480 --> 00:27:37.120
they gave me money
to send arms to the Mujahideen.

437
00:27:37.680 --> 00:27:41.880
Then they gave me money to bring
the arms back from the Mujahideen.

438
00:27:42.480 --> 00:27:45.199
Now I have the arms. I have the money.

439
00:27:45.200 --> 00:27:47.000
and the Americans have gone.

440
00:27:49.880 --> 00:27:51.200
We're here to do a deal.

441
00:27:52.840 --> 00:27:53.960
That's all.

442
00:27:56.480 --> 00:27:59.200
Yes. that is all.

443
00:28:02.880 --> 00:28:09.240
The British army. the Russians.
the Americans did not just have a plan.

444
00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:11.640
They had a cause.

445
00:28:14.400 --> 00:28:17.040
But you men. you have no cause.

446
00:28:21.960 --> 00:28:23.560
You have no

447
00:28:24.280 --> 00:28:25.559
soul.

448
00:28:25.560 --> 00:28:27.359
[man gasping]

449
00:28:27.360 --> 00:28:28.919
When I look at you…

450
00:28:28.920 --> 00:28:30.319
[man shouting in Pashto]

451
00:28:30.320 --> 00:28:31.320
…I see ghosts.

452
00:28:34.120 --> 00:28:35.519
But that is okay.

453
00:28:35.520 --> 00:28:37.959
- These mountains are full of ghosts.
- [man whimpers]

454
00:28:37.960 --> 00:28:40.040
There's always room for more.

455
00:28:48.680 --> 00:28:49.760
[exhales]

456
00:28:57.400 --> 00:28:59.119
You have come a long way.

457
00:28:59.120 --> 00:29:02.920
Now you must rest while I talk to Hakan.

458
00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:06.599
[Guy] Jesus Christ.

459
00:29:06.600 --> 00:29:09.760
You must not worry about that.
It was a show of strength.

460
00:29:10.360 --> 00:29:12.400
Now we must show him ours.

461
00:29:14.320 --> 00:29:15.960
Can we trust Hakan?

462
00:29:16.480 --> 00:29:18.680
[sighs] Hakan is an old king.

463
00:29:19.480 --> 00:29:22.240
There is nothing more dangerous
than an old king.

464
00:29:22.760 --> 00:29:24.480
They want a final victory.

465
00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:29.080
and there is no fear and no limits
in what they will do to achieve it.

466
00:29:29.760 --> 00:29:34.200
If we show we can help Hakan win
a final victory. we are safe.

467
00:29:35.240 --> 00:29:38.120
If we don't. we are not.

468
00:29:39.520 --> 00:29:40.559
- Back.
- [Guy] What?

469
00:29:40.560 --> 00:29:41.719
You go back.

470
00:29:41.720 --> 00:29:43.960
What do you think we're gonna do. mate?
Walk to England?

471
00:29:45.200 --> 00:29:46.240
Back!

472
00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:51.000
Go!

473
00:29:53.800 --> 00:29:55.800
[quiet. mournful music playing]

474
00:29:56.600 --> 00:29:58.840
We must all show that we can help.

475
00:29:59.360 --> 00:30:01.320
- Mmm.
- Yeah.

476
00:30:20.160 --> 00:30:21.800
[camel bellows]

477
00:30:38.280 --> 00:30:39.680
Afghanistan.

478
00:30:40.680 --> 00:30:42.040
[in Pashto] I know.

479
00:31:08.840 --> 00:31:10.400
[exhales shakily]

480
00:31:40.360 --> 00:31:42.120
[sighs] Papa.

481
00:31:43.080 --> 00:31:45.080
[sobs] Oh. Papa.

482
00:31:47.160 --> 00:31:48.480
[sniffles]

483
00:32:00.240 --> 00:32:02.120
[in Pashto] I know who you are.

484
00:32:09.640 --> 00:32:11.840
Long live the king!

485
00:32:13.560 --> 00:32:15.440
Long live the king!

486
00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:24.160
You are home.

487
00:32:25.520 --> 00:32:26.720
Your Highness.

488
00:32:34.280 --> 00:32:35.280
[music fades]

489
00:32:36.200 --> 00:32:37.360
[children chattering]

490
00:32:38.200 --> 00:32:40.200
[in English] What do we do
if Guy doesn't come back?

491
00:32:40.720 --> 00:32:41.880
You know. kid.

492
00:32:42.920 --> 00:32:45.359
you're the one that's been
the hardest to work out.

493
00:32:45.360 --> 00:32:47.599
- Why's that?
- I thought I had you sussed.

494
00:32:47.600 --> 00:32:50.400
Crap job in Customs.
bored out of your skull.

495
00:32:50.920 --> 00:32:52.639
now's your chance for a bit of excitement.

496
00:32:52.640 --> 00:32:54.960
And then I saw where you went to school.

497
00:32:56.520 --> 00:32:58.080
I just can't get my head around that.

498
00:32:59.240 --> 00:33:00.760
[horns beeping]

499
00:33:02.080 --> 00:33:04.400
I got a scholarship through the church.

500
00:33:07.600 --> 00:33:11.240
[chuckles] And even then.
the uniform cost my dad a week's wages.

501
00:33:12.520 --> 00:33:14.480
But they were so happy. man. [chuckles]

502
00:33:15.200 --> 00:33:19.920
Only a few years off the boat.
and their son going to a school like that.

503
00:33:20.440 --> 00:33:24.520
"Where Britain finds its leaders."
That's what the brochure said.

504
00:33:26.640 --> 00:33:27.640
But…

505
00:33:29.960 --> 00:33:31.560
no one else looked like me.

506
00:33:32.520 --> 00:33:35.560
Some of them couldn't get past that.
Not just the kids.

507
00:33:36.840 --> 00:33:39.920
I tried to help.
I'd speak one way at home.

508
00:33:40.440 --> 00:33:41.760
another way there.

509
00:33:43.680 --> 00:33:45.920
But the closer I tried to get to them…

510
00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:49.680
the further away I ended up.

511
00:33:51.640 --> 00:33:55.960
They said if I sat my A-levels.
I'd endanger their average.

512
00:33:56.800 --> 00:33:58.200
And so here I am.

513
00:34:01.560 --> 00:34:04.880
That lot weren't fit
to lace your boots. son.

514
00:34:06.440 --> 00:34:08.239
I've never felt a part of something.

515
00:34:08.240 --> 00:34:10.999
You're a part of something now.
and if we pull this off.

516
00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:14.640
you'll have done more for Britain than
every kid from that school put together.

517
00:34:16.760 --> 00:34:18.520
And if Guy doesn't come back.

518
00:34:20.040 --> 00:34:21.040
we'll go and get him.

519
00:34:25.360 --> 00:34:30.920
[Afridi] 2.000 years. that is how long
it has taken to create the Silk Road.

520
00:34:31.840 --> 00:34:37.319
From China to Turkey. the greatest
trading route the world has ever seen.

521
00:34:37.320 --> 00:34:40.359
Our section is the Khyber Pass.

522
00:34:40.360 --> 00:34:43.280
You take the goods. you pass them on.

523
00:34:44.040 --> 00:34:47.439
You trust the other sections.
you trust the Silk Road.

524
00:34:47.440 --> 00:34:49.840
you trust the 2.000 years.

525
00:34:51.080 --> 00:34:54.119
Now you are asking me
to trust you instead.

526
00:34:54.120 --> 00:34:56.280
to abandon everything I know.

527
00:34:57.680 --> 00:34:58.880
Why?

528
00:35:03.320 --> 00:35:04.840
Because your road's fucked.

529
00:35:07.920 --> 00:35:10.160
You've lost your contact in Istanbul.

530
00:35:10.680 --> 00:35:13.719
If you can't move your opium on
from Istanbul.

531
00:35:13.720 --> 00:35:15.720
you might as well leave it in the fields.

532
00:35:16.240 --> 00:35:18.120
How would you move it?

533
00:35:18.640 --> 00:35:22.080
Boat. which is quicker. cheaper. safer.

534
00:35:22.600 --> 00:35:25.200
More money for you.
and we'll be back sooner for more.

535
00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:28.800
[quiet. tense music playing]

536
00:35:30.200 --> 00:35:31.879
[sighs]

537
00:35:31.880 --> 00:35:35.839
[Afridi] Hakan. you and I are
servants of history.

538
00:35:35.840 --> 00:35:39.719
but these men are drug dealers

539
00:35:39.720 --> 00:35:41.279
who I do not know.

540
00:35:41.280 --> 00:35:43.680
No. We're businessmen.

541
00:35:49.640 --> 00:35:52.879
[in Pashto] You can leave.
Hakan. but they cannot.

542
00:35:52.880 --> 00:35:55.640
[man shouting in Pashto in distance]

543
00:36:04.280 --> 00:36:06.120
[whispering]

544
00:36:25.120 --> 00:36:26.360
[music fades]

545
00:36:28.240 --> 00:36:30.000
[in English] You look like your mother.

546
00:36:32.240 --> 00:36:34.880
Thank you. I miss her.

547
00:36:36.720 --> 00:36:38.680
We were loyal to your father.

548
00:36:40.440 --> 00:36:41.640
He came to me

549
00:36:43.040 --> 00:36:44.720
the night before it happened.

550
00:36:45.680 --> 00:36:48.000
He told me it would happen.

551
00:36:49.240 --> 00:36:50.800
but he would not let it happen to me.

552
00:36:55.480 --> 00:36:57.520
When they surrounded the palace.

553
00:36:58.280 --> 00:37:00.160
I was already in the mountains.

554
00:37:02.240 --> 00:37:03.240
Your mountains.

555
00:37:06.280 --> 00:37:07.640
And my father

556
00:37:08.160 --> 00:37:11.480
would have never sent me
through these mountains. Afridi.

557
00:37:12.520 --> 00:37:14.480
without your protection.

558
00:37:15.400 --> 00:37:19.040
We were loyal to the man. not the crown.

559
00:37:19.560 --> 00:37:22.600
The Pashtun do not recognize kings.

560
00:37:24.640 --> 00:37:26.800
He did not need to wear a crown

561
00:37:27.560 --> 00:37:28.840
to be a king.

562
00:37:41.560 --> 00:37:43.239
[sighs]

563
00:37:43.240 --> 00:37:44.440
Very well.

564
00:37:45.680 --> 00:37:48.720
I cannot say no to Hakan and a princess.

565
00:37:49.240 --> 00:37:52.279
Gentlemen. you will leave here tomorrow

566
00:37:52.280 --> 00:37:56.240
with two tonnes
of the finest opium in the world.

567
00:37:57.000 --> 00:37:58.480
I wish you luck.

568
00:37:59.960 --> 00:38:01.920
And I think you will need it.

569
00:38:04.840 --> 00:38:06.280
[music fades]

570
00:38:14.600 --> 00:38:18.360
Hiya. I'm from Customs. up from London.
I need to check a record.

571
00:38:18.960 --> 00:38:23.399
That's an intergovernmental request.
I get them from the liaison office.

572
00:38:23.400 --> 00:38:24.920
Well. you're getting it from me.

573
00:38:27.080 --> 00:38:29.119
As long as you've got the paperwork.

574
00:38:29.120 --> 00:38:32.360
We're in a fast-moving situation.
I'll get it back to you tomorrow.

575
00:38:36.680 --> 00:38:38.440
Miserable out there. isn't it?

576
00:38:39.120 --> 00:38:42.319
The rain. the drugs. the guns.

577
00:38:42.320 --> 00:38:44.399
I can't blame the rain. that's geography.

578
00:38:44.400 --> 00:38:47.520
That's us gettin' it in the neck
from the Atlantic. But the rest?

579
00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:50.719
I'll tell you. love. it's no fun out there

580
00:38:50.720 --> 00:38:53.079
if you're daft enough
to wear a uniform like this.

581
00:38:53.080 --> 00:38:55.840
which makes this job as good as it gets.

582
00:38:56.520 --> 00:38:59.159
But if a record leaves this office
without the paperwork.

583
00:38:59.160 --> 00:39:02.000
then I lose this job
and I'm back out there

584
00:39:02.520 --> 00:39:06.000
with the rain and the drugs and the guns.

585
00:39:06.680 --> 00:39:08.839
All for the sake of some sort
up from London.

586
00:39:08.840 --> 00:39:10.000
[Kate chuckles]

587
00:39:11.160 --> 00:39:12.160
I get it.

588
00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:17.000
How about
if the record doesn't go anywhere?

589
00:39:17.520 --> 00:39:19.319
Let me read it here. Just five minutes.

590
00:39:19.320 --> 00:39:21.480
And then you can forget
I was ever even here.

591
00:39:23.080 --> 00:39:24.040
[sighs]

592
00:39:25.040 --> 00:39:27.480
- What's the name?
- Declan Carter.

593
00:39:28.520 --> 00:39:30.160
- Wait here.
- Thank you.

594
00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:34.000
[quiet. suspenseful music playing]

595
00:39:53.040 --> 00:39:55.040
[footsteps approach]

596
00:39:57.600 --> 00:39:58.800
[Goodwin] Hello. love.

597
00:40:01.400 --> 00:40:02.800
Come with me. please.

598
00:40:15.080 --> 00:40:17.679
If Customs wanna know about Declan Carter.

599
00:40:17.680 --> 00:40:20.400
it's an unusual way to go about it.

600
00:40:21.880 --> 00:40:26.120
I think Declan Carter and Liverpool police
might be an unusual situation.

601
00:40:31.240 --> 00:40:33.800
I've waited for this for a long time

602
00:40:34.440 --> 00:40:36.999
because I've known Declan Carter
for a long time.

603
00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:39.079
And I know him well enough
and this city well enough

604
00:40:39.080 --> 00:40:41.799
to know that you don't go
from running nightclub doors

605
00:40:41.800 --> 00:40:44.359
to running a vast criminal network

606
00:40:44.360 --> 00:40:48.319
without a little bit of help
from someone inside this building.

607
00:40:48.320 --> 00:40:49.759
Help from who?

608
00:40:49.760 --> 00:40:51.160
I don't know.

609
00:40:52.520 --> 00:40:56.640
I know it's not some PC on the beat
that he's slung a few quid to.

610
00:40:57.440 --> 00:40:58.920
There's plenty of them.

611
00:40:59.440 --> 00:41:04.080
But I reckon Carter's got someone in here
with a bit of clout.

612
00:41:04.920 --> 00:41:06.560
And they're hard to get to.

613
00:41:07.480 --> 00:41:09.880
And trying to get to them
is a dangerous game.

614
00:41:11.120 --> 00:41:14.119
I hope that's not a threat.
If it is. we're gonna have a problem.

615
00:41:14.120 --> 00:41:16.279
I put the note in Carter's record

616
00:41:16.280 --> 00:41:18.679
to try and catch whoever
was messing around with it.

617
00:41:18.680 --> 00:41:20.920
Looks like I caught an ally instead.

618
00:41:22.240 --> 00:41:23.680
And I'll help you.

619
00:41:24.200 --> 00:41:25.560
but it's just me.

620
00:41:26.160 --> 00:41:28.879
No one else inside here I trust with this.

621
00:41:28.880 --> 00:41:30.280
[quiet. ominous music playing]

622
00:41:34.920 --> 00:41:36.320
I want his police record.

623
00:41:37.240 --> 00:41:38.720
Okay. I can get you that.

624
00:41:40.200 --> 00:41:42.919
As far as I can see.
they've covered their tracks.

625
00:41:42.920 --> 00:41:45.600
but maybe you can see
something in there that I can't.

626
00:41:51.560 --> 00:41:54.399
And keep my name out of your system.

627
00:41:54.400 --> 00:41:57.080
and meet me here later.

628
00:41:58.440 --> 00:42:00.280
I'll get you everything you need.

629
00:42:04.080 --> 00:42:06.040
- Thanks for your help.
- Okay.

630
00:42:07.640 --> 00:42:09.640
[grasshoppers chirping]

631
00:42:11.280 --> 00:42:13.280
[footsteps approaching]

632
00:42:20.560 --> 00:42:22.919
[Hakan] We are from mountains like these.

633
00:42:22.920 --> 00:42:24.520
people like these.

634
00:42:25.040 --> 00:42:27.280
It feels like home here.

635
00:42:29.280 --> 00:42:30.440
Does it not?

636
00:42:30.960 --> 00:42:32.040
Not for me.

637
00:42:34.440 --> 00:42:37.720
You know.
the Kurds and the Pashtun are brothers.

638
00:42:38.480 --> 00:42:40.880
We fought together many times.

639
00:42:41.480 --> 00:42:42.560
And now.

640
00:42:44.080 --> 00:42:46.080
we are together again.

641
00:42:56.360 --> 00:42:59.560
Afridi will give me his poppies.

642
00:43:03.880 --> 00:43:05.680
And I will give him my son.

643
00:43:09.840 --> 00:43:11.160
What does that mean?

644
00:43:12.640 --> 00:43:13.960
Watch Guy.

645
00:43:14.720 --> 00:43:16.519
Learn what you need to learn.

646
00:43:16.520 --> 00:43:19.560
When the drugs get to England. he goes.

647
00:43:20.200 --> 00:43:23.480
And you will live here in Pakistan
and work with Afridi.

648
00:43:24.040 --> 00:43:25.120
Together.

649
00:43:26.120 --> 00:43:28.320
we will be unstoppable.

650
00:43:30.440 --> 00:43:31.960
You want me to live here?

651
00:43:34.520 --> 00:43:35.680
Uh. here?

652
00:43:36.200 --> 00:43:39.600
Where I know no one?
Where I sleep with the fucking goats?

653
00:43:41.480 --> 00:43:44.279
I'm getting old. Aziz. and I have failed.

654
00:43:44.280 --> 00:43:46.800
My only son has forgotten who he is.

655
00:43:50.440 --> 00:43:51.840
You will live here.

656
00:43:53.400 --> 00:43:54.560
A Kurd

657
00:43:55.280 --> 00:43:56.880
amongst the Pashtun.

658
00:44:00.360 --> 00:44:02.680
And you will remember who you are.

659
00:44:06.240 --> 00:44:07.519
And if I say no?

660
00:44:07.520 --> 00:44:09.200
You're my son.

661
00:44:09.880 --> 00:44:12.840
I let you do things no one else can.

662
00:44:13.360 --> 00:44:16.240
Question me. Argue with me.

663
00:44:17.040 --> 00:44:20.359
You have freedom. Aziz.
More freedom than I ever had.

664
00:44:20.360 --> 00:44:21.960
You can do many things.

665
00:44:23.080 --> 00:44:24.840
But you cannot say no.

666
00:44:36.960 --> 00:44:38.440
[man speaking Pashto]

667
00:44:50.640 --> 00:44:52.040
[Aziz] Why do you do this?

668
00:44:54.040 --> 00:44:57.999
You're a clever man.
You can do anything. and… you do this.

669
00:44:58.000 --> 00:44:59.880
I could ask you the same thing.

670
00:45:03.160 --> 00:45:04.920
I don't wanna do this forever.

671
00:45:08.160 --> 00:45:11.600
Maybe. in London.
we can talk about other things we can do.

672
00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:14.520
Other business.

673
00:45:15.640 --> 00:45:16.840
Real business.

674
00:45:18.400 --> 00:45:19.720
Yeah. we can do that.

675
00:45:21.120 --> 00:45:22.000
Good.

676
00:45:29.280 --> 00:45:31.280
[quiet. tense music playing]

677
00:45:38.160 --> 00:45:40.000
[engine starts]

678
00:45:40.520 --> 00:45:41.640
[Carter] Is your boat ready?

679
00:45:42.760 --> 00:45:44.080
Yeah. course.

680
00:45:45.400 --> 00:45:46.640
We'll come with you.

681
00:45:47.600 --> 00:45:48.760
To the docks.

682
00:45:49.560 --> 00:45:50.560
[Guy] No.

683
00:45:54.320 --> 00:45:55.320
You what?

684
00:45:59.120 --> 00:46:01.640
The less people at the docks.
the better. [scoffs]

685
00:46:03.960 --> 00:46:05.320
That's a lot of drugs.

686
00:46:07.640 --> 00:46:09.080
And it's a lot of money.

687
00:46:11.200 --> 00:46:13.320
And I still don't fucking know
who you are.

688
00:46:15.960 --> 00:46:17.520
So we'll be coming with you.

689
00:46:19.120 --> 00:46:20.480
To the docks.

690
00:46:23.960 --> 00:46:24.960
Fair enough.

691
00:46:25.480 --> 00:46:27.520
About time you got your hands dirty.

692
00:46:31.400 --> 00:46:34.000
- [hits truck twice]
- Speak with Afridi's men.

693
00:46:36.320 --> 00:46:37.920
- Get yourself a piece.
- [engine starts]

694
00:46:52.200 --> 00:46:54.200
[tense music continues]

695
00:46:55.520 --> 00:46:57.520
[water dripping]

696
00:47:16.560 --> 00:47:18.360
[Goodwin] You shouldn't have come here.

697
00:47:19.440 --> 00:47:21.440
Liverpool. You shouldn't have come.

698
00:47:23.400 --> 00:47:26.280
You don't understand
how things work around here.

699
00:47:28.240 --> 00:47:30.280
You think things are black and white.

700
00:47:30.800 --> 00:47:32.599
Right and wrong.
goodies and fuckin' baddies.

701
00:47:32.600 --> 00:47:34.080
That's not Liverpool. Never has been.

702
00:47:36.080 --> 00:47:40.039
My old man worked on the Queen's Docks.
14-hour shifts. half-day Saturday.

703
00:47:40.040 --> 00:47:45.080
and at the end of the week. there'd be
a box to take home off the boats.

704
00:47:45.920 --> 00:47:48.160
Sugar. booze.

705
00:47:49.400 --> 00:47:50.920
Pineapple one week.

706
00:47:52.680 --> 00:47:55.480
And the copper who covered the docks.

707
00:47:56.280 --> 00:47:59.080
he'd get two boxes.
'cause that's how it worked.

708
00:48:00.520 --> 00:48:03.040
- How did Carter get to you?
- You're not listenin'.

709
00:48:04.080 --> 00:48:06.879
This is how it works.

710
00:48:06.880 --> 00:48:08.719
I keep Carter in check.

711
00:48:08.720 --> 00:48:10.919
Things would be
a hell of a lot worse if I didn't.

712
00:48:10.920 --> 00:48:14.880
I have stopped bloody murders.

713
00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:19.359
- And you'd get me ten years for it.
- Work with me.

714
00:48:19.360 --> 00:48:22.640
There's not many ways out of this. love.
That isn't one of them.

715
00:48:27.240 --> 00:48:29.120
18 Moult Street.

716
00:48:32.200 --> 00:48:34.320
That's a house that tells a story. Arthur.

717
00:48:34.960 --> 00:48:37.239
Bought for cash. twice your salary.

718
00:48:37.240 --> 00:48:42.240
and then mortgaged to the hilt
to use as security against all that debt.

719
00:48:46.120 --> 00:48:48.680
I look at your house. and I see weakness.

720
00:48:49.600 --> 00:48:51.920
I look at your house. and I see Carter.

721
00:48:53.800 --> 00:48:58.079
Since when did Customs decide
they could take on the bloody world?

722
00:48:58.080 --> 00:49:00.200
You don't know the half of it. mate.

723
00:49:03.080 --> 00:49:04.520
This is your fault.

724
00:49:05.720 --> 00:49:08.639
It's not mine. You shouldn't have come.

725
00:49:08.640 --> 00:49:10.919
- Support needed.
- [crashing]

726
00:49:10.920 --> 00:49:13.279
- [officer 1] Armed police!
- [officer 2] Don't move!

727
00:49:13.280 --> 00:49:16.400
- [officer 3] Hands where they are!
- [officer 4] Armed police! Do not move!

728
00:49:22.920 --> 00:49:25.039
I'm not gonna tell you anything.

729
00:49:25.040 --> 00:49:27.520
You're in no state
to tell anyone anything.

730
00:49:29.080 --> 00:49:30.360
You need rest.

731
00:49:31.480 --> 00:49:32.999
You need clarity.

732
00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:35.879
And you'll get it
in a police cell in Manchester.

733
00:49:35.880 --> 00:49:38.320
under fake charges. under a fake name.

734
00:49:39.520 --> 00:49:42.240
And when that clarity arrives. Arthur.

735
00:49:43.920 --> 00:49:45.920
you will tell me everything I need.

736
00:49:49.680 --> 00:49:50.760
Nick him.

737
00:49:53.120 --> 00:49:54.839
[Goodwin] All right. settle down.

738
00:49:54.840 --> 00:49:57.239
You can stop pointing that at me
for a fuckin' start.

739
00:49:57.240 --> 00:49:59.319
- [handcuffs click]
- [Goodwin groans]

740
00:49:59.320 --> 00:50:01.320
[tense music continues]

741
00:50:03.760 --> 00:50:05.760
[breathing shakily]

742
00:50:09.320 --> 00:50:10.680
[sighs]

743
00:50:26.680 --> 00:50:28.680
[tense music continues]

744
00:50:53.880 --> 00:50:56.399
- <i>Assalamu alaikum.</i>
- [guard 1] <i>Wa alaikum. Jawed.</i>

745
00:50:56.400 --> 00:50:58.400
[speaking Pashto]

746
00:51:08.040 --> 00:51:09.840
Where the fuck's he going?

747
00:51:17.120 --> 00:51:18.080
Oi!

748
00:51:19.320 --> 00:51:20.680
Piss off out of it.

749
00:51:23.880 --> 00:51:25.000
[guard 1] Hey!

750
00:51:32.920 --> 00:51:34.920
[breathing heavily]

751
00:51:35.800 --> 00:51:37.319
[music fades]

752
00:51:37.320 --> 00:51:40.999
Hundred million quid's worth of heroin.
and you can't get us a proper boat?

753
00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:43.359
- [ship's horn blares]
- It looks all right to me. Pete.

754
00:51:43.360 --> 00:51:46.959
Power's on the blink. navigation's shot.
and we're about to take on a journey

755
00:51:46.960 --> 00:51:49.119
without a friendly coastline
for 800 nautical miles.

756
00:51:49.120 --> 00:51:51.880
- [phone ringing]
- It's a long way from all right. Don.

757
00:51:56.400 --> 00:51:58.999
- You're alive. then?
- We're comin' in now.

758
00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:02.280
<i>- What do you mean. now?</i>
- I mean fuckin' now.

759
00:52:14.560 --> 00:52:15.600
Let's go.

760
00:52:22.880 --> 00:52:25.199
- [Don] He's comin' in.
- We can't leave. We need a few days.

761
00:52:25.200 --> 00:52:27.799
- He's coming now. We've gotta go.
- [Pete] It's too dangerous.

762
00:52:27.800 --> 00:52:29.360
[guards speaking Pashto]

763
00:52:31.120 --> 00:52:33.120
[suspenseful music playing]

764
00:53:04.560 --> 00:53:06.039
Hurry up with that winch!

765
00:53:06.040 --> 00:53:09.159
Get that load on sharpish.
and start the engines.

766
00:53:09.160 --> 00:53:12.119
[man] All right. you heard him.
Get it started. Let's go.

767
00:53:12.120 --> 00:53:14.040
- [ship's horn blasts]
- [Carter] What's the plan?

768
00:53:14.560 --> 00:53:18.719
Get that lot on a boat. fly back.
meet it in Felixstowe.

769
00:53:18.720 --> 00:53:21.520
get it through Customs.
and none of us have to work again.

770
00:53:23.520 --> 00:53:26.360
What kind of drug smuggler
doesn't travel with the drugs?

771
00:53:35.600 --> 00:53:39.080
Fine. I just fuckin' hate boats.

772
00:53:40.560 --> 00:53:43.680
- You're in the wrong job. then.
- Tell me about it.

773
00:53:44.720 --> 00:53:45.639
[claps]

774
00:53:45.640 --> 00:53:48.480
Come on! Let's move it!

775
00:53:49.840 --> 00:53:51.040
Go with him.

776
00:53:54.400 --> 00:53:55.400
No.

777
00:53:59.080 --> 00:54:00.080
You know. Eddie.

778
00:54:01.240 --> 00:54:03.000
you never used to say no to me.

779
00:54:04.520 --> 00:54:06.399
- Now it's all you say.
- [music fades]

780
00:54:06.400 --> 00:54:08.360
We've come a long way. Carter.

781
00:54:09.280 --> 00:54:11.240
I'm just trying to get us to the end.

782
00:54:12.120 --> 00:54:13.399
That's all.

783
00:54:13.400 --> 00:54:15.400
["Infinity" by Guru Josh playing]

784
00:54:20.520 --> 00:54:22.560
[engine starts]

785
00:54:29.080 --> 00:54:30.600
[Bailey] Guy's going with the load.

786
00:54:34.440 --> 00:54:35.639
That wasn't the plan.

787
00:54:35.640 --> 00:54:36.840
[Don sighs]

788
00:54:38.600 --> 00:54:40.840
[Don] It's not about having a plan. son.

789
00:54:42.600 --> 00:54:44.280
Anyone can have a plan.

790
00:54:45.920 --> 00:54:47.159
In this game.

791
00:54:47.160 --> 00:54:49.360
it's about having control.

792
00:54:50.760 --> 00:54:52.640
And I reckon we just lost that.

793
00:54:56.200 --> 00:54:58.520
["Infinity" continues]

794
00:56:08.200 --> 00:56:09.480
[music fades]
